\
I went up to the flat wondering what Brett had done to the concierge.\
The wire was a cable from Bill Gorton, saying he was arriving on the\
_France_. I put the mail on the table, went back to the bedroom,\
undressed and had a shower. I was rubbing down when I heard the\
door-bell pull. I put on a bathrobe and slippers and went to the door.\
It was Brett. Back of her was the count. He was holding a great bunch of\
roses.\
\
\'93Hello, darling,\'94 said Brett. \'93Aren\'92t you going to let us in?\'94\
\
\'93Come on. I was just bathing.\'94\
\
\'93Aren\'92t you the fortunate man. Bathing.\'94\
\
\'93Only a shower. Sit down, Count Mippipopolous. What will you drink?\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t know whether you like flowers, sir,\'94 the count said, \'93but I\
took the liberty of just bringing these roses.\'94\
\
\'93Here, give them to me.\'94 Brett took them. \'93Get me some water in this,\
Jake.\'94 I filled the big earthenware jug with water in the kitchen, and\
Brett put the roses in it, and placed them in the centre of the\
dining-room table.\
\
\'93I say. We have had a day.\'94\
\
\'93You don\'92t remember anything about a date with me at the Crillon?\'94\
\
\'93No. Did we have one? I must have been blind.\'94\
\
\'93You were quite drunk, my dear,\'94 said the count.\
\
\'93Wasn\'92t I, though? And the count\'92s been a brick, absolutely.\'94\
\
\'93You\'92ve got hell\'92s own drag with the concierge now.\'94\
\
\'93I ought to have. Gave her two hundred francs.\'94\
\
\'93Don\'92t be a damned fool.\'94\
\
\'93His,\'94 she said, and nodded at the count.\
\
\'93I thought we ought to give her a little something for last night. It\
was very late.\'94\
\
\'93He\'92s wonderful,\'94 Brett said. \'93He remembers everything that\'92s happened.\'94\
\
\'93So do you, my dear.\'94\
\
\'93Fancy,\'94 said Brett. \'93Who\'92d want to? I say, Jake, _do_ we get a drink?\'94\
\
\'93You get it while I go in and dress. You know where it is.\'94\
\
\'93Rather.\'94\
\
While I dressed I heard Brett put down glasses and then a siphon, and\
then heard them talking. I dressed slowly, sitting on the bed. I felt\
tired and pretty rotten. Brett came in the room, a glass in her hand,\
and sat on the bed.\
\
\'93What\'92s the matter, darling? Do you feel rocky?\'94\
\
She kissed me coolly on the forehead.\
\
\'93Oh, Brett, I love you so much.\'94\
\
\'93Darling,\'94 she said. Then: \'93Do you want me to send him away?\'94\
\
\'93No. He\'92s nice.\'94\
\
\'93I\'92ll send him away.\'94\
\
\'93No, don\'92t.\'94\
\
\'93Yes, I\'92ll send him away.\'94\
\
\'93You can\'92t just like that.\'94\
\
\'93Can\'92t I, though? You stay here. He\'92s mad about me, I tell you.\'94\
\
She was gone out of the room. I lay face down on the bed. I was having a\
bad time. I heard them talking but I did not listen. Brett came in and\
sat on the bed.\
\
\'93Poor old darling.\'94 She stroked my head.\
\
\'93What did you say to him?\'94 I was lying with my face away from her. I did\
not want to see her.\
\
\'93Sent him for champagne. He loves to go for champagne.\'94\
\
Then later: \'93Do you feel better, darling? Is the head any better?\'94\
\
\'93It\'92s better.\'94\
\
\'93Lie quiet. He\'92s gone to the other side of town.\'94\
\
\'93Couldn\'92t we live together, Brett? Couldn\'92t we just live together?\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t think so. I\'92d just _tromper_ you with everybody. You couldn\'92t\
stand it.\'94\
\
\'93I stand it now.\'94\
\
\'93That would be different. It\'92s my fault, Jake. It\'92s the way I\'92m made.\'94\
\
\'93Couldn\'92t we go off in the country for a while?\'94\
\
\'93It wouldn\'92t be any good. I\'92ll go if you like. But I couldn\'92t live\
quietly in the country. Not with my own true love.\'94\
\
\'93I know.\'94\
\
\'93Isn\'92t it rotten? There isn\'92t any use my telling you I love you.\'94\
\
\'93You know I love you.\'94\
\
\'93Let\'92s not talk. Talking\'92s all bilge. I\'92m going away from you, and then\
Michael\'92s coming back.\'94\
\
\'93Why are you going away?\'94\
\
\'93Better for you. Better for me.\'94\
\
\'93When are you going?\'94\
\
\'93Soon as I can.\'94\
\
\'93Where?\'94\
\
\'93San Sebastian.\'94\
\
\'93Can\'92t we go together?\'94\
\
\'93No. That would be a hell of an idea after we\'92d just talked it out.\'94\
\
\'93We never agreed.\'94\
\
\'93Oh, you know as well as I do. Don\'92t be obstinate, darling.\'94\
\
\'93Oh, sure,\'94 I said. \'93I know you\'92re right. I\'92m just low, and when I\'92m low\
I talk like a fool.\'94\
\
I sat up, leaned over, found my shoes beside the bed and put them on. I\
stood up.\
\
\'93Don\'92t look like that, darling.\'94\
\
\'93How do you want me to look?\'94\
\
\'93Oh, don\'92t be a fool. I\'92m going away to-morrow.\'94\
\
\'93To-morrow?\'94\
\
\'93Yes. Didn\'92t I say so? I am.\'94\
\
\'93Let\'92s have a drink, then. The count will be back.\'94\
\
\'93Yes. He should be back. You know he\'92s extraordinary about buying\
champagne. It means any amount to him.\'94\
\
We went into the dining-room. I took up the brandy bottle and poured\
Brett a drink and one for myself. There was a ring at the bell-pull. I\
went to the door and there was the count. Behind him was the chauffeur\
carrying a basket of champagne.\
\
\'93Where should I have him put it, sir?\'94 asked the count.\
\
\'93In the kitchen,\'94 Brett said.\
\
\'93Put it in there, Henry,\'94 the count motioned. \'93Now go down and get the\
ice.\'94 He stood looking after the basket inside the kitchen door. \'93I\
think you\'92ll find that\'92s very good wine,\'94 he said. \'93I know we don\'92t get\
much of a chance to judge good wine in the States now, but I got this\
