\
\'93No. What a pity.\'94\
\
\'93No,\'94 said the count. \'93You don\'92t need a title. You got class all over\
you.\'94\
\
\'93Thanks. Awfully decent of you.\'94\
\
\'93I\'92m not joking you,\'94 the count blew a cloud of smoke. \'93You got the most\
class of anybody I ever seen. You got it. That\'92s all.\'94\
\
\'93Nice of you,\'94 said Brett. \'93Mummy would be pleased. Couldn\'92t you write\
it out, and I\'92ll send it in a letter to her.\'94\
\
\'93I\'92d tell her, too,\'94 said the count. \'93I\'92m not joking you. I never joke\
people. Joke people and you make enemies. That\'92s what I always say.\'94\
\
\'93You\'92re right,\'94 Brett said. \'93You\'92re terribly right. I always joke people\
and I haven\'92t a friend in the world. Except Jake here.\'94\
\
\'93You don\'92t joke him.\'94\
\
\'93That\'92s it.\'94\
\
\'93Do you, now?\'94 asked the count. \'93Do you joke him?\'94\
\
Brett looked at me and wrinkled up the corners of her eyes.\
\
\'93No,\'94 she said. \'93I wouldn\'92t joke him.\'94\
\
\'93See,\'94 said the count. \'93You don\'92t joke him.\'94\
\
\'93This is a hell of a dull talk,\'94 Brett said. \'93How about some of that\
