\
\'93Drunk? Drunk?\'94\
\
\'93My dear, you are charming when you are drunk.\'94\
\
\'93Listen to the man.\'94\
\
\'93Mr. Barnes,\'94 the count poured my glass full. \'93She is the only lady I\
have ever known who was as charming when she was drunk as when she was\
sober.\'94\
\
\'93You haven\'92t been around much, have you?\'94\
\
\'93Yes, my dear. I have been around very much. I have been around a very\
great deal.\'94\
\
\'93Drink your wine,\'94 said Brett. \'93We\'92ve all been around. I dare say Jake\
here has seen as much as you have.\'94\
\
\'93My dear, I am sure Mr. Barnes has seen a lot. Don\'92t think I don\'92t think\
so, sir. I have seen a lot, too.\'94\
\
\'93Of course you have, my dear,\'94 Brett said. \'93I was only ragging.\'94\
\
\'93I have been in seven wars and four revolutions,\'94 the count said.\
\
\'93Soldiering?\'94 Brett asked.\
\
\'93Sometimes, my dear. And I have got arrow wounds. Have you ever seen\
arrow wounds?\'94\
\
\'93Let\'92s have a look at them.\'94\
\
The count stood up, unbuttoned his vest, and opened his shirt. He pulled\
up the undershirt onto his chest and stood, his chest black, and big\
stomach muscles bulging under the light.\
\
\'93You see them?\'94\
\
Below the line where his ribs stopped were two raised white welts. \'93See\
on the back where they come out.\'94 Above the small of the back were the\
same two scars, raised as thick as a finger.\
\
\'93I say. Those are something.\'94\
\
\'93Clean through.\'94\
\
The count was tucking in his shirt.\
\
\'93Where did you get those?\'94 I asked.\
\
\'93In Abyssinia. When I was twenty-one years old.\'94\
\
\'93What were you doing?\'94 asked Brett. \'93Were you in the army?\'94\
\
\'93I was on a business trip, my dear.\'94\
\
\'93I told you he was one of us. Didn\'92t I?\'94 Brett turned to me. \'93I love\
you, count. You\'92re a darling.\'94\
\
\'93You make me very happy, my dear. But it isn\'92t true.\'94\
\
\'93Don\'92t be an ass.\'94\
\
\'93You see, Mr. Barnes, it is because I have lived very much that now I\
can enjoy everything so well. Don\'92t you find it like that?\'94\
\
\'93Yes. Absolutely.\'94\
\
\'93I know,\'94 said the count. \'93That is the secret. You must get to know the\
values.\'94\
\
\'93Doesn\'92t anything ever happen to your values?\'94 Brett asked.\
\
\'93No. Not any more.\'94\
\
\'93Never fall in love?\'94\
\
\'93Always,\'94 said the count. \'93I am always in love.\'94\
\
\'93What does that do to your values?\'94\
\
\'93That, too, has got a place in my values.\'94\
\
\'93You haven\'92t any values. You\'92re dead, that\'92s all.\'94\
\
\'93No, my dear. You\'92re not right. I\'92m not dead at all.\'94\
\
We drank three bottles of the champagne and the count left the basket in\
my kitchen. We dined at a restaurant in the Bois. It was a good dinner.\
Food had an excellent place in the count\'92s values. So did wine. The\
count was in fine form during the meal. So was Brett. It was a good\
party.\
\
\'93Where would you like to go?\'94 asked the count after dinner. We were the\
only people left in the restaurant. The two waiters were standing over\
against the door. They wanted to go home.\
\
\'93We might go up on the hill,\'94 Brett said. \'93Haven\'92t we had a splendid\
party?\'94\
\
The count was beaming. He was very happy.\
\
\'93You are very nice people,\'94 he said. He was smoking a cigar again. \'93Why\
don\'92t you get married, you two?\'94\
\
\'93We want to lead our own lives,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93We have our careers,\'94 Brett said. \'93Come on. Let\'92s get out of this.\'94\
\
\'93Have another brandy,\'94 the count said.\
\
\'93Get it on the hill.\'94\
\
\'93No. Have it here where it is quiet.\'94\
\
\'93You and your quiet,\'94 said Brett. \'93What is it men feel about quiet?\'94\
\
\'93We like it,\'94 said the count. \'93Like you like noise, my dear.\'94\
\
\'93All right,\'94 said Brett. \'93Let\'92s have one.\'94\
\
\'93Sommelier!\'94 the count called.\
\
\'93Yes, sir.\'94\
\
\'93What is the oldest brandy you have?\'94\
\
\'93Eighteen eleven, sir.\'94\
\
\'93Bring us a bottle.\'94\
\
\'93I say. Don\'92t be ostentatious. Call him off, Jake.\'94\
\
\'93Listen, my dear. I get more value for my money in old brandy than in\
any other antiquities.\'94\
\
\'93Got many antiquities?\'94\
\
\'93I got a houseful.\'94\
\
Finally we went up to Montmartre. Inside Zelli\'92s it was crowded, smoky,\
and noisy. The music hit you as you went in. Brett and I danced. It was\
so crowded we could barely move. The nigger drummer waved at Brett. We\
were caught in the jam, dancing in one place in front of him.\
\
\'93Hahre you?\'94\
\
\'93Great.\'94\
\
\'93Thaats good.\'94\
\
He was all teeth and lips.\
\
\'93He\'92s a great friend of mine,\'94 Brett said. \'93Damn good drummer.\'94\
\
The music stopped and we started toward the table where the count sat.\
Then the music started again and we danced. I looked at the count. He\
was sitting at the table smoking a cigar. The music stopped again.\
\
\'93Let\'92s go over.\'94\
\
Brett started toward the table. The music started and again we danced,\
tight in the crowd.\
\
\'93You are a rotten dancer, Jake. Michael\'92s the best dancer I know.\'94\
\
\'93He\'92s splendid.\'94\
\
\'93He\'92s got his points.\'94\
\
\'93I like him,\'94 I said. \'93I\'92m damned fond of him.\'94\
\
\'93I\'92m going to marry him,\'94 Brett said. \'93Funny. I haven\'92t thought about\
him for a week.\'94\
\
\'93Don\'92t you write him?\'94\
\
\'93Not I. Never write letters.\'94\
\
\'93I\'92ll bet he writes to you.\'94\
\
\'93Rather. Damned good letters, too.\'94\
\
\'93When are you going to get married?\'94\
\
\'93How do I know? As soon as we can get the divorce. Michael\'92s trying to\
get his mother to put up for it.\'94\
\
\'93Could I help you?\'94\
\
\'93Don\'92t be an ass. Michael\'92s people have loads of money.\'94\
\
The music stopped. We walked over to the table. The count stood up.\
\
\'93Very nice,\'94 he said. \'93You looked very, very nice.\'94\
\
\'93Don\'92t you dance, count?\'94 I asked.\
\
\'93No. I\'92m too old.\'94\
\
\'93Oh, come off it,\'94 Brett said.\
\
\'93My dear, I would do it if I would enjoy it. I enjoy to watch you\
dance.\'94\
\
\'93Splendid,\'94 Brett said. \'93I\'92ll dance again for you some time. I say. What\
about your little friend, Zizi?\'94\
\
\'93Let me tell you. I support that boy, but I don\'92t want to have him\
around.\'94\
\
\'93He is rather hard.\'94\
\
\'93You know I think that boy\'92s got a future. But personally I don\'92t want\
him around.\'94\
\
\'93Jake\'92s rather the same way.\'94\
\
\'93He gives me the willys.\'94\
\
\'93Well,\'94 the count shrugged his shoulders. \'93About his future you can\'92t\
ever tell. Anyhow, his father was a great friend of my father.\'94\
\
\'93Come on. Let\'92s dance,\'94 Brett said.\
\
We danced. It was crowded and close.\
\
\'93Oh, darling,\'94 Brett said, \'93I\'92m so miserable.\'94\
\
I had that feeling of going through something that has all happened\
before. \'93You were happy a minute ago.\'94\
\
The drummer shouted: \'93You can\'92t two time\'97\'94\
\
\'93It\'92s all gone.\'94\
\
\'93What\'92s the matter?\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t know. I just feel terribly.\'94\
\
\'93. . . . . .\'94 the drummer chanted. Then turned to his sticks.\
\
\'93Want to go?\'94\
\
I had the feeling as in a nightmare of it all being something repeated,\
something I had been through and that now I must go through again.\
\
\'93. . . . . .\'94 the drummer sang softly.\
\
\'93Let\'92s go,\'94 said Brett. \'93You don\'92t mind.\'94\
\
\'93. . . . . .\'94 the drummer shouted and grinned at Brett.\
\
\'93All right,\'94 I said. We got out from the crowd. Brett went to the\
dressing-room.\
\
\'93Brett wants to go,\'94 I said to the count. He nodded. \'93Does she? That\'92s\
fine. You take the car. I\'92m going to stay here for a while, Mr. Barnes.\'94\
\
We shook hands.\
\
\'93It was a wonderful time,\'94 I said. \'93I wish you would let me get this.\'94 I\
took a note out of my pocket.\
\
\'93Mr. Barnes, don\'92t be ridiculous,\'94 the count said.\
\
Brett came over with her wrap on. She kissed the count and put her hand\
on his shoulder to keep him from standing up. As we went out the door I\
looked back and there were three girls at his table. We got into the big\
car. Brett gave the chauffeur the address of her hotel.\
\
\'93No, don\'92t come up,\'94 she said at the hotel. She had rung and the door\
was unlatched.\
\
\'93Really?\'94\
\
\'93No. Please.\'94\
\
\'93Good night, Brett,\'94 I said. \'93I\'92m sorry you feel rotten.\'94\
\
\'93Good night, Jake. Good night, darling. I won\'92t see you again.\'94 We\
kissed standing at the door. She pushed me away. We kissed again. \'93Oh,\
don\'92t!\'94 Brett said.\
\
She turned quickly and went into the hotel. The chauffeur drove me\
around to my flat. I gave him twenty francs and he touched his cap and\
said: \'93Good night, sir,\'94 and drove off. I rang the bell. The door opened\
and I went up-stairs and went to bed.\
\
\
\
\
                                BOOK II\
\
\
\
\
                                CHAPTER\
                                   8\
\
\
I did not see Brett again until she came back from San Sebastian. One\
card came from her from there. It had a picture of the Concha, and said:\
\'93Darling. Very quiet and healthy. Love to all the chaps. BRETT.\'94\
\
Nor did I see Robert Cohn again. I heard Frances had left for England\
and I had a note from Cohn saying he was going out in the country for a\
couple of weeks, he did not know where, but that he wanted to hold me to\
the fishing-trip in Spain we had talked about last winter. I could reach\
him always, he wrote, through his bankers.\
\
Brett was gone, I was not bothered by Cohn\'92s troubles, I rather enjoyed\
not having to play tennis, there was plenty of work to do, I went often\
to the races, dined with friends, and put in some extra time at the\
office getting things ahead so I could leave it in charge of my\
secretary when Bill Gorton and I should shove off to Spain the end of\
June. Bill Gorton arrived, put up a couple of days at the flat and went\
off to Vienna. He was very cheerful and said the States were wonderful.\
New York was wonderful. There had been a grand theatrical season and a\
whole crop of great young light heavyweights. Any one of them was a good\
prospect to grow up, put on weight and trim Dempsey. Bill was very\
happy. He had made a lot of money on his last book, and was going to\
make a lot more. We had a good time while he was in Paris, and then he\
went off to Vienna. He was coming back in three weeks and we would leave\
for Spain to get in some fishing and go to the fiesta at Pamplona. He\
wrote that Vienna was wonderful. Then a card from Budapest: \'93Jake,\
Budapest is wonderful.\'94 Then I got a wire: \'93Back on Monday.\'94\
\
Monday evening he turned up at the flat. I heard his taxi stop and went\
to the window and called to him; he waved and started up-stairs carrying\
his bags. I met him on the stairs, and took one of the bags.\
\
\'93Well,\'94 I said, \'93I hear you had a wonderful trip.\'94\
\
\'93Wonderful,\'94 he said. \'93Budapest is absolutely wonderful.\'94\
\
\'93How about Vienna?\'94\
\
\'93Not so good, Jake. Not so good. It seemed better than it was.\'94\
\
\'93How do you mean?\'94 I was getting glasses and a siphon.\
\
\'93Tight, Jake. I was tight.\'94\
\
\'93That\'92s strange. Better have a drink.\'94\
\
Bill rubbed his forehead. \'93Remarkable thing,\'94 he said. \'93Don\'92t know how\
it happened. Suddenly it happened.\'94\
\
\'93Last long?\'94\
\
\'93Four days, Jake. Lasted just four days.\'94\
\
\'93Where did you go?\'94\
\
\'93Don\'92t remember. Wrote you a post-card. Remember that perfectly.\'94\
\
\'93Do anything else?\'94\
\
\'93Not so sure. Possible.\'94\
\
\'93Go on. Tell me about it.\'94\
\
\'93Can\'92t remember. Tell you anything I could remember.\'94\
\
\'93Go on. Take that drink and remember.\'94\
\
\'93Might remember a little,\'94 Bill said. \'93Remember something about a\
prize-fight. Enormous Vienna prize-fight. Had a nigger in it. Remember\
the nigger perfectly.\'94\
\
\'93Go on.\'94\
\
\'93Wonderful nigger. Looked like Tiger Flowers, only four times as big.\
All of a sudden everybody started to throw things. Not me. Nigger\'92d just\
knocked local boy down. Nigger put up his glove. Wanted to make a\
speech. Awful noble-looking nigger. Started to make a speech. Then local\
white boy hit him. Then he knocked white boy cold. Then everybody\
commenced to throw chairs. Nigger went home with us in our car. Couldn\'92t\
get his clothes. Wore my coat. Remember the whole thing now. Big\
sporting evening.\'94\
\
\'93What happened?\'94\
\
\'93Loaned the nigger some clothes and went around with him to try and get\
his money. Claimed nigger owed them money on account of wrecking hall.\
Wonder who translated? Was it me?\'94\
\
\'93Probably it wasn\'92t you.\'94\
\
\'93You\'92re right. Wasn\'92t me at all. Was another fellow. Think we called him\
the local Harvard man. Remember him now. Studying music.\'94\
\
\'93How\'92d you come out?\'94\
\
\'93Not so good, Jake. Injustice everywhere. Promoter claimed nigger\
promised let local boy stay. Claimed nigger violated contract. Can\'92t\
knock out Vienna boy in Vienna. \'91My God, Mister Gorton,\'92 said nigger, \'91I\
didn\'92t do nothing in there for forty minutes but try and let him stay.\
That white boy musta ruptured himself swinging at me. I never did hit\
him.\'92\'94\
\
\'93Did you get any money?\'94\
\
\'93No money, Jake. All we could get was nigger\'92s clothes. Somebody took\
his watch, too. Splendid nigger. Big mistake to have come to Vienna. Not\
so good, Jake. Not so good.\'94\
\
\'93What became of the nigger?\'94\
\
\'93Went back to Cologne. Lives there. Married. Got a family. Going to\
write me a letter and send me the money I loaned him. Wonderful nigger.\
Hope I gave him the right address.\'94\
\
\'93You probably did.\'94\
\
\'93Well, anyway, let\'92s eat,\'94 said Bill. \'93Unless you want me to tell you\
some more travel stories.\'94\
\
\'93Go on.\'94\
\
\'93Let\'92s eat.\'94\
\
We went down-stairs and out onto the Boulevard St. Michel in the warm\
June evening.\
\
\'93Where will we go?\'94\
\
\'93Want to eat on the island?\'94\
\
\'93Sure.\'94\
\
We walked down the Boulevard. At the juncture of the Rue\
Denfert-Rochereau with the Boulevard is a statue of two men in flowing\
robes.\
\
\'93I know who they are.\'94 Bill eyed the monument. \'93Gentlemen who invented\
pharmacy. Don\'92t try and fool me on Paris.\'94\
\
We went on.\
\
\'93Here\'92s a taxidermist\'92s,\'94 Bill said. \'93Want to buy anything? Nice stuffed\
dog?\'94\
\
\'93Come on,\'94 I said. \'93You\'92re pie-eyed.\'94\
\
\'93Pretty nice stuffed dogs,\'94 Bill said. \'93Certainly brighten up your\
flat.\'94\
\
\'93Come on.\'94\
\
\'93Just one stuffed dog. I can take \'92em or leave \'92em alone. But listen,\
Jake. Just one stuffed dog.\'94\
\
\'93Come on.\'94\
\
\'93Mean everything in the world to you after you bought it. Simple\
exchange of values. You give them money. They give you a stuffed dog.\'94\
\
\'93We\'92ll get one on the way back.\'94\
\
\'93All right. Have it your own way. Road to hell paved with unbought\
stuffed dogs. Not my fault.\'94\
\
We went on.\
\
\'93How\'92d you feel that way about dogs so sudden?\'94\
\
\'93Always felt that way about dogs. Always been a great lover of stuffed\
animals.\'94\
\
We stopped and had a drink.\
\
\'93Certainly like to drink,\'94 Bill said. \'93You ought to try it some times,\
Jake.\'94\
\
\'93You\'92re about a hundred and forty-four ahead of me.\'94\
\
\'93Ought not to daunt you. Never be daunted. Secret of my success. Never\
been daunted. Never been daunted in public.\'94\
\
\'93Where were you drinking?\'94\
\
\'93Stopped at the Crillon. George made me a couple of Jack Roses. George\'92s\
a great man. Know the secret of his success? Never been daunted.\'94\
\
\'93You\'92ll be daunted after about three more pernods.\'94\
\
\'93Not in public. If I begin to feel daunted I\'92ll go off by myself. I\'92m\
like a cat that way.\'94\
\
\'93When did you see Harvey Stone?\'94\
\
\'93At the Crillon. Harvey was just a little daunted. Hadn\'92t eaten for\
three days. Doesn\'92t eat any more. Just goes off like a cat. Pretty sad.\'94\
\
\'93He\'92s all right.\'94\
\
\'93Splendid. Wish he wouldn\'92t keep going off like a cat, though. Makes me\
nervous.\'94\
\
\'93What\'92ll we do to-night?\'94\
\
\'93Doesn\'92t make any difference. Only let\'92s not get daunted. Suppose they\
got any hard-boiled eggs here? If they had hard-boiled eggs here we\
wouldn\'92t have to go all the way down to the island to eat.\'94\
\
\'93Nix,\'94 I said. \'93We\'92re going to have a regular meal.\'94\
\
\'93Just a suggestion,\'94 said Bill. \'93Want to start now?\'94\
\
\'93Come on.\'94\
\
We started on again down the Boulevard. A horse-cab passed us. Bill\
looked at it.\
\
\'93See that horse-cab? Going to have that horse-cab stuffed for you for\
Christmas. Going to give all my friends stuffed animals. I\'92m a\
nature-writer.\'94\
\
A taxi passed, some one in it waved, then banged for the driver to stop.\
The taxi backed up to the curb. In it was Brett.\
\
\'93Beautiful lady,\'94 said Bill. \'93Going to kidnap us.\'94\
\
\'93Hullo!\'94 Brett said. \'93Hullo!\'94\
\
\'93This is Bill Gorton. Lady Ashley.\'94\
\
Brett smiled at Bill. \'93I say I\'92m just back. Haven\'92t bathed even. Michael\
comes in to-night.\'94\
\
\'93Good. Come on and eat with us, and we\'92ll all go to meet him.\'94\
\
\'93Must clean myself.\'94\
\
\'93Oh, rot! Come on.\'94\
\
\'93Must bathe. He doesn\'92t get in till nine.\'94\
\
\'93Come and have a drink, then, before you bathe.\'94\
\
\'93Might do that. Now you\'92re not talking rot.\'94\
\
We got in the taxi. The driver looked around.\
\
\'93Stop at the nearest bistro,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93We might as well go to the Closerie,\'94 Brett said. \'93I can\'92t drink these\
rotten brandies.\'94\
\
\'93Closerie des Lilas.\'94\
\
Brett turned to Bill.\
\
\'93Have you been in this pestilential city long?\'94\
\
\'93Just got in to-day from Budapest.\'94\
\
\'93How was Budapest?\'94\
\
\'93Wonderful. Budapest was wonderful.\'94\
\
\'93Ask him about Vienna.\'94\
\
\'93Vienna,\'94 said Bill, \'93is a strange city.\'94\
\
\'93Very much like Paris,\'94 Brett smiled at him, wrinkling the corners of\
her eyes.\
\
\'93Exactly,\'94 Bill said. \'93Very much like Paris at this moment.\'94\
\
\'93You _have_ a good start.\'94\
\
Sitting out on the terraces of the Lilas Brett ordered a whiskey and\
soda, I took one, too, and Bill took another pernod.\
\
\'93How are you, Jake?\'94\
\
\'93Great,\'94 I said. \'93I\'92ve had a good time.\'94\
\
Brett looked at me. \'93I was a fool to go away,\'94 she said. \'93One\'92s an ass\
to leave Paris.\'94\
\
\'93Did you have a good time?\'94\
\
\'93Oh, all right. Interesting. Not frightfully amusing.\'94\
\
\'93See anybody?\'94\
\
\'93No, hardly anybody. I never went out.\'94\
\
\'93Didn\'92t you swim?\'94\
\
\'93No. Didn\'92t do a thing.\'94\
\
\'93Sounds like Vienna,\'94 Bill said.\
\
Brett wrinkled up the corners of her eyes at him.\
\
\'93So that\'92s the way it was in Vienna.\'94\
\
\'93It was like everything in Vienna.\'94\
\
Brett smiled at him again.\
\
\'93You\'92ve a nice friend, Jake.\'94\
\
\'93He\'92s all right,\'94 I said. \'93He\'92s a taxidermist.\'94\
\
\'93That was in another country,\'94 Bill said. \'93And besides all the animals\
were dead.\'94\
\
\'93One more,\'94 Brett said, \'93and I must run. Do send the waiter for a taxi.\'94\
\
\'93There\'92s a line of them. Right out in front.\'94\
\
\'93Good.\'94\
\
We had the drink and put Brett into her taxi.\
\
\'93Mind you\'92re at the Select around ten. Make him come. Michael will be\
there.\'94\
\
\'93We\'92ll be there,\'94 Bill said. The taxi started and Brett waved.\
\
\'93Quite a girl,\'94 Bill said. \'93She\'92s damned nice. Who\'92s Michael?\'94\
\
\'93The man she\'92s going to marry.\'94\
\
\'93Well, well,\'94 Bill said. \'93That\'92s always just the stage I meet anybody.\
What\'92ll I send them? Think they\'92d like a couple of stuffed race-horses?\'94\
\
\'93We better eat.\'94\
\
\'93Is she really Lady something or other?\'94 Bill asked in the taxi on our\
way down to the Ile Saint Louis.\
\
\'93Oh, yes. In the stud-book and everything.\'94\
\
\'93Well, well.\'94\
\
We ate dinner at Madame Lecomte\'92s restaurant on the far side of the\
island. It was crowded with Americans and we had to stand up and wait\
for a place. Some one had put it in the American Women\'92s Club list as a\
quaint restaurant on the Paris quais as yet untouched by Americans, so\
we had to wait forty-five minutes for a table. Bill had eaten at the\
restaurant in 1918, and right after the armistice, and Madame Lecomte\
made a great fuss over seeing him.\
\
\'93Doesn\'92t get us a table, though,\'94 Bill said. \'93Grand woman, though.\'94\
\
We had a good meal, a roast chicken, new green beans, mashed potatoes, a\
salad, and some apple-pie and cheese.\
\
\'93You\'92ve got the world here all right,\'94 Bill said to Madame Lecomte. She\
raised her hand. \'93Oh, my God!\'94\
\
\'93You\'92ll be rich.\'94\
\
\'93I hope so.\'94\
\
After the coffee and a _fine_ we got the bill, chalked up the same as\
ever on a slate, that was doubtless one of the \'93quaint\'94 features, paid\
it, shook hands, and went out.\
\
\'93You never come here any more, Monsieur Barnes,\'94 Madame Lecomte said.\
\
\'93Too many compatriots.\'94\
\
\'93Come at lunch-time. It\'92s not crowded then.\'94\
\
\'93Good. I\'92ll be down soon.\'94\
\
We walked along under the trees that grew out over the river on the Quai\
d\'92Orl\'e9ans side of the island. Across the river were the broken walls of\
old houses that were being torn down.\
\
\'93They\'92re going to cut a street through.\'94\
\
\'93They would,\'94 Bill said.\
\
We walked on and circled the island. The river was dark and a bateau\
mouche went by, all bright with lights, going fast and quiet up and out\
of sight under the bridge. Down the river was Notre Dame squatting\
against the night sky. We crossed to the left bank of the Seine by the\
wooden foot-bridge from the Quai de Bethune, and stopped on the bridge\
and looked down the river at Notre Dame. Standing on the bridge the\
island looked dark, the houses were high against the sky, and the trees\
were shadows.\
\
\'93It\'92s pretty grand,\'94 Bill said. \'93God, I love to get back.\'94\
\
We leaned on the wooden rail of the bridge and looked up the river to\
the lights of the big bridges. Below the water was smooth and black. It\
made no sound against the piles of the bridge. A man and a girl passed\
us. They were walking with their arms around each other.\
\
We crossed the bridge and walked up the Rue du Cardinal Lemoine. It was\
steep walking, and we went all the way up to the Place Contrescarpe. The\
arc-light shone through the leaves of the trees in the square, and\
underneath the trees was an S bus ready to start. Music came out of the\
