\
\'93Nothing until the fifth.\'94\
\
\'93What\'92s this?\'94\
\
There were never more than two servings of lunch on that train, and\
always plenty of places for both of them.\
\
\'93They\'92re all reserved,\'94 the dining-car conductor said. \'93There will be a\
fifth service at three-thirty.\'94\
\
\'93This is serious,\'94 I said to Bill.\
\
\'93Give him ten francs.\'94\
\
\'93Here,\'94 I said. \'93We want to eat in the first service.\'94\
\
The conductor put the ten francs in his pocket.\
\
\'93Thank you,\'94 he said. \'93I would advise you gentlemen to get some\
sandwiches. All the places for the first four services were reserved at\
the office of the company.\'94\
\
\'93You\'92ll go a long way, brother,\'94 Bill said to him in English. \'93I suppose\
if I\'92d given you five francs you would have advised us to jump off the\
train.\'94\
\
\'93_Comment?_\'94\
\
\'93Go to hell!\'94 said Bill. \'93Get the sandwiches made and a bottle of wine.\
You tell him, Jake.\'94\
\
\'93And send it up to the next car.\'94 I described where we were.\
