them all off their backing\'97you know, they put them on a strip\'97and gave\
them all around. Gave one to each girl. Form of souvenir. They thought I\
was hell\'92s own shakes of a soldier. Give away medals in a night club.\
Dashing fellow.\'94\
\
\'93Tell the rest,\'94 Brett said.\
\
\'93Don\'92t you think that was funny?\'94 Mike asked. We were all laughing. \'93It\
was. I swear it was. Any rate, my tailor wrote me and wanted the medals\
back. Sent a man around. Kept on writing for months. Seems some chap had\
left them to be cleaned. Frightfully military cove. Set hell\'92s own store\
by them.\'94 Mike paused. \'93Rotten luck for the tailor,\'94 he said.\
\
\'93You don\'92t mean it,\'94 Bill said. \'93I should think it would have been grand\
for the tailor.\'94\
\
\'93Frightfully good tailor. Never believe it to see me now,\'94 Mike said. \'93I\
used to pay him a hundred pounds a year just to keep him quiet. So he\
wouldn\'92t send me any bills. Frightful blow to him when I went bankrupt.\
It was right after the medals. Gave his letters rather a bitter tone.\'94\
\
\'93How did you go bankrupt?\'94 Bill asked.\
\
\'93Two ways,\'94 Mike said. \'93Gradually and then suddenly.\'94\
\
\'93What brought it on?\'94\
\
\'93Friends,\'94 said Mike. \'93I had a lot of friends. False friends. Then I had\
creditors, too. Probably had more creditors than anybody in England.\'94\
\
\'93Tell them about in the court,\'94 Brett said.\
\
\'93I don\'92t remember,\'94 Mike said. \'93I was just a little tight.\'94\
\
\'93Tight!\'94 Brett exclaimed. \'93You were blind!\'94\
\
\'93Extraordinary thing,\'94 Mike said. \'93Met my former partner the other day.\
Offered to buy me a drink.\'94\
\
\'93Tell them about your learned counsel,\'94 Brett said.\
\
\'93I will not,\'94 Mike said. \'93My learned counsel was blind, too. I say this\
is a gloomy subject. Are we going down and see these bulls unloaded or\
not?\'94\
\
\'93Let\'92s go down.\'94\
\
We called the waiter, paid, and started to walk through the town. I\
started off walking with Brett, but Robert Cohn came up and joined her\
on the other side. The three of us walked along, past the Ayuntamiento\
with the banners hung from the balcony, down past the market and down\
past the steep street that led to the bridge across the Arga. There were\
many people walking to go and see the bulls, and carriages drove down\
the hill and across the bridge, the drivers, the horses, and the whips\
rising above the walking people in the street. Across the bridge we\
turned up a road to the corrals. We passed a wine-shop with a sign in\
the window: Good Wine 30 Centimes A Liter.\
\
\'93That\'92s where we\'92ll go when funds get low,\'94 Brett said.\
\
The woman standing in the door of the wine-shop looked at us as we\
passed. She called to some one in the house and three girls came to the\
window and stared. They were staring at Brett.\
\
At the gate of the corrals two men took tickets from the people that\
went in. We went in through the gate. There were trees inside and a low,\
stone house. At the far end was the stone wall of the corrals, with\
apertures in the stone that were like loopholes running all along the\
face of each corral. A ladder led up to the top of the wall, and people\
were climbing up the ladder and spreading down to stand on the walls\
that separated the two corrals. As we came up the ladder, walking across\
the grass under the trees, we passed the big, gray painted cages with\
the bulls in them. There was one bull in each travelling-box. They had\
come by train from a bull-breeding ranch in Castile, and had been\
unloaded off flat-cars at the station and brought up here to be let out\
of their cages into the corrals. Each cage was stencilled with the name\
and the brand of the bull-breeder.\
\
We climbed up and found a place on the wall looking down into the\
corral. The stone walls were whitewashed, and there was straw on the\
ground and wooden feed-boxes and water-troughs set against the wall.\
\
\'93Look up there,\'94 I said.\
\
Beyond the river rose the plateau of the town. All along the old walls\
and ramparts people were standing. The three lines of fortifications\
made three black lines of people. Above the walls there were heads in\
the windows of the houses. At the far end of the plateau boys had\
climbed into the trees.\
\
\'93They must think something is going to happen,\'94 Brett said.\
\
\'93They want to see the bulls.\'94\
\
Mike and Bill were on the other wall across the pit of the corral. They\
waved to us. People who had come late were standing behind us, pressing\
against us when other people crowded them.\
\
\'93Why don\'92t they start?\'94 Robert Cohn asked.\
\
A single mule was hitched to one of the cages and dragged it up against\
the gate in the corral wall. The men shoved and lifted it with crowbars\
into position against the gate. Men were standing on the wall ready to\
pull up the gate of the corral and then the gate of the cage. At the\
other end of the corral a gate opened and two steers came in, swaying\
their heads and trotting, their lean flanks swinging. They stood\
together at the far end, their heads toward the gate where the bull\
would enter.\
\
\'93They don\'92t look happy,\'94 Brett said.\
\
The men on top of the wall leaned back and pulled up the door of the\
corral. Then they pulled up the door of the cage.\
\
I leaned way over the wall and tried to see into the cage. It was dark.\
Some one rapped on the cage with an iron bar. Inside something seemed to\
explode. The bull, striking into the wood from side to side with his\
horns, made a great noise. Then I saw a dark muzzle and the shadow of\
horns, and then, with a clattering on the wood in the hollow box, the\
bull charged and came out into the corral, skidding with his forefeet in\
the straw as he stopped, his head up, the great hump of muscle on his\
neck swollen tight, his body muscles quivering as he looked up at the\
crowd on the stone walls. The two steers backed away against the wall,\
their heads sunken, their eyes watching the bull.\
\
The bull saw them and charged. A man shouted from behind one of the\
boxes and slapped his hat against the planks, and the bull, before he\
reached the steer, turned, gathered himself and charged where the man\
had been, trying to reach him behind the planks with a half-dozen quick,\
searching drives with the right horn.\
\
\'93My God, isn\'92t he beautiful?\'94 Brett said. We were looking right down on\
him.\
\
\'93Look how he knows how to use his horns,\'94 I said. \'93He\'92s got a left and a\
right just like a boxer.\'94\
\
\'93Not really?\'94\
\
\'93You watch.\'94\
\
\'93It goes too fast.\'94\
\
\'93Wait. There\'92ll be another one in a minute.\'94\
\
They had backed up another cage into the entrance. In the far corner a\
man, from behind one of the plank shelters, attracted the bull, and\
while the bull was facing away the gate was pulled up and a second bull\
came out into the corral.\
\
He charged straight for the steers and two men ran out from behind the\
planks and shouted, to turn him. He did not change his direction and the\
men shouted: \'93Hah! Hah! Toro!\'94 and waved their arms; the two steers\
turned sideways to take the shock, and the bull drove into one of the\
steers.\
\
\'93Don\'92t look,\'94 I said to Brett. She was watching, fascinated.\
\
\'93Fine,\'94 I said. \'93If it doesn\'92t buck you.\'94\
\
\'93I saw it,\'94 she said. \'93I saw him shift from his left to his right horn.\'94\
\
\'93Damn good!\'94\
\
The steer was down now, his neck stretched out, his head twisted, he lay\
the way he had fallen. Suddenly the bull left off and made for the other\
steer which had been standing at the far end, his head swinging,\
watching it all. The steer ran awkwardly and the bull caught him, hooked\
him lightly in the flank, and then turned away and looked up at the\
crowd on the walls, his crest of muscle rising. The steer came up to him\
and made as though to nose at him and the bull hooked perfunctorily. The\
next time he nosed at the steer and then the two of them trotted over to\
the other bull.\
\
When the next bull came out, all three, the two bulls and the steer,\
stood together, their heads side by side, their horns against the\
newcomer. In a few minutes the steer picked the new bull up, quieted him\
down, and made him one of the herd. When the last two bulls had been\
unloaded the herd were all together.\
\
The steer who had been gored had gotten to his feet and stood against\
the stone wall. None of the bulls came near him, and he did not attempt\
to join the herd.\
\
We climbed down from the wall with the crowd, and had a last look at the\
bulls through the loopholes in the wall of the corral. They were all\
quiet now, their heads down. We got a carriage outside and rode up to\
the caf\'e9. Mike and Bill came in half an hour later. They had stopped on\
the way for several drinks.\
\
We were sitting in the caf\'e9.\
\
\'93That\'92s an extraordinary business,\'94 Brett said.\
\
\'93Will those last ones fight as well as the first?\'94 Robert Cohn asked.\
\'93They seemed to quiet down awfully fast.\'94\
\
\'93They all know each other,\'94 I said. \'93They\'92re only dangerous when they\'92re\
alone, or only two or three of them together.\'94\
\
\'93What do you mean, dangerous?\'94 Bill said. \'93They all looked dangerous to\
me.\'94\
\
\'93They only want to kill when they\'92re alone. Of course, if you went in\
there you\'92d probably detach one of them from the herd, and he\'92d be\
dangerous.\'94\
\
\'93That\'92s too complicated,\'94 Bill said. \'93Don\'92t you ever detach me from the\
herd, Mike.\'94\
\
\'93I say,\'94 Mike said, \'93they _were_ fine bulls, weren\'92t they? Did you see\
their horns?\'94\
\
\'93Did I not,\'94 said Brett. \'93I had no idea what they were like.\'94\
\
\'93Did you see the one hit that steer?\'94 Mike asked. \'93That was\
extraordinary.\'94\
\
\'93It\'92s no life being a steer,\'94 Robert Cohn said.\
\
\'93Don\'92t you think so?\'94 Mike said. \'93I would have thought you\'92d loved being\
a steer, Robert.\'94\
\
\'93What do you mean, Mike?\'94\
\
\'93They lead such a quiet life. They never say anything and they\'92re always\
hanging about so.\'94\
\
We were embarrassed. Bill laughed. Robert Cohn was angry. Mike went on\
talking.\
\
\'93I should think you\'92d love it. You\'92d never have to say a word. Come on,\
Robert. Do say something. Don\'92t just sit there.\'94\
\
\'93I said something, Mike. Don\'92t you remember? About the steers.\'94\
\
\'93Oh, say something more. Say something funny. Can\'92t you see we\'92re all\
having a good time here?\'94\
\
\'93Come off it, Michael. You\'92re drunk,\'94 Brett said.\
\
\'93I\'92m not drunk. I\'92m quite serious. _Is_ Robert Cohn going to follow\
Brett around like a steer all the time?\'94\
\
\'93Shut up, Michael. Try and show a little breeding.\'94\
\
\'93Breeding be damned. Who has any breeding, anyway, except the bulls?\
Aren\'92t the bulls lovely? Don\'92t you like them, Bill? Why don\'92t you say\
something, Robert? Don\'92t sit there looking like a bloody funeral. What\
if Brett did sleep with you? She\'92s slept with lots of better people than\
you.\'94\
\
\'93Shut up,\'94 Cohn said. He stood up. \'93Shut up, Mike.\'94\
\
\'93Oh, don\'92t stand up and act as though you were going to hit me. That\
won\'92t make any difference to me. Tell me, Robert. Why do you follow\
Brett around like a poor bloody steer? Don\'92t you know you\'92re not wanted?\
I know when I\'92m not wanted. Why don\'92t you know when you\'92re not wanted?\
You came down to San Sebastian where you weren\'92t wanted, and followed\
Brett around like a bloody steer. Do you think that\'92s right?\'94\
\
\'93Shut up. You\'92re drunk.\'94\
\
\'93Perhaps I am drunk. Why aren\'92t you drunk? Why don\'92t you ever get drunk,\
Robert? You know you didn\'92t have a good time at San Sebastian because\
none of our friends would invite you on any of the parties. You can\'92t\
blame them hardly. Can you? I asked them to. They wouldn\'92t do it. You\
can\'92t blame them, now. Can you? Now, answer me. Can you blame them?\'94\
\
\'93Go to hell, Mike.\'94\
\
\'93I can\'92t blame them. Can you blame them? Why do you follow Brett around?\
Haven\'92t you any manners? How do you think it makes _me_ feel?\'94\
\
\'93You\'92re a splendid one to talk about manners,\'94 Brett said. \'93You\'92ve such\
lovely manners.\'94\
\
\'93Come on, Robert,\'94 Bill said.\
\
\'93What do you follow her around for?\'94\
\
Bill stood up and took hold of Cohn.\
\
\'93Don\'92t go,\'94 Mike said. \'93Robert Cohn\'92s going to buy a drink.\'94\
\
Bill went off with Cohn. Cohn\'92s face was sallow. Mike went on talking. I\
sat and listened for a while. Brett looked disgusted.\
\
\'93I say, Michael, you might not be such a bloody ass,\'94 she interrupted.\
\'93I\'92m not saying he\'92s not right, you know.\'94 She turned to me.\
\
The emotion left Mike\'92s voice. We were all friends together.\
\
\'93I\'92m not so damn drunk as I sounded,\'94 he said.\
\
\'93I know you\'92re not,\'94 Brett said.\
\
\'93We\'92re none of us sober,\'94 I said.\
\
\'93I didn\'92t say anything I didn\'92t mean.\'94\
\
\'93But you put it so badly,\'94 Brett laughed.\
\
\'93He was an ass, though. He came down to San Sebastian where he damn well\
wasn\'92t wanted. He hung around Brett and just _looked_ at her. It made me\
damned well sick.\'94\
\
\'93He did behave very badly,\'94 Brett said.\
\
\'93Mark you. Brett\'92s had affairs with men before. She tells me all about\
everything. She gave me this chap Cohn\'92s letters to read. I wouldn\'92t\
read them.\'94\
\
\'93Damned noble of you.\'94\
\
\'93No, listen, Jake. Brett\'92s gone off with men. But they weren\'92t ever\
Jews, and they didn\'92t come and hang about afterward.\'94\
\
\'93Damned good chaps,\'94 Brett said. \'93It\'92s all rot to talk about it. Michael\
and I understand each other.\'94\
\
\'93She gave me Robert Cohn\'92s letters. I wouldn\'92t read them.\'94\
\
\'93You wouldn\'92t read any letters, darling. You wouldn\'92t read mine.\'94\
\
\'93I can\'92t read letters,\'94 Mike said. \'93Funny, isn\'92t it?\'94\
\
\'93You can\'92t read anything.\'94\
\
\'93No. You\'92re wrong there. I read quite a bit. I read when I\'92m at home.\'94\
\
\'93You\'92ll be writing next,\'94 Brett said. \'93Come on, Michael. Do buck up.\
You\'92ve got to go through with this thing now. He\'92s here. Don\'92t spoil the\
fiesta.\'94\
\
\'93Well, let him behave, then.\'94\
\
\'93He\'92ll behave. I\'92ll tell him.\'94\
\
\'93You tell him, Jake. Tell him either he must behave or get out.\'94\
\
\'93Yes,\'94 I said, \'93it would be nice for me to tell him.\'94\
\
\'93Look, Brett. Tell Jake what Robert calls you. That is perfect, you\
know.\'94\
\
\'93Oh, no. I can\'92t.\'94\
\
\'93Go on. We\'92re all friends. Aren\'92t we all friends, Jake?\'94\
\
\'93I can\'92t tell him. It\'92s too ridiculous.\'94\
\
\'93I\'92ll tell him.\'94\
\
\'93You won\'92t, Michael. Don\'92t be an ass.\'94\
\
\'93He calls her Circe,\'94 Mike said. \'93He claims she turns men into swine.\
Damn good. I wish I were one of these literary chaps.\'94\
\
\'93He\'92d be good, you know,\'94 Brett said. \'93He writes a good letter.\'94\
\
\'93I know,\'94 I said. \'93He wrote me from San Sebastian.\'94\
\
\'93That was nothing,\'94 Brett said. \'93He can write a damned amusing letter.\'94\
\
\'93She made me write that. She was supposed to be ill.\'94\
\
\'93I damned well was, too.\'94\
\
\'93Come on,\'94 I said, \'93we must go in and eat.\'94\
\
\'93How should I meet Cohn?\'94 Mike said.\
\
\'93Just act as though nothing had happened.\'94\
\
\'93It\'92s quite all right with me,\'94 Mike said. \'93I\'92m not embarrassed.\'94\
\
\'93If he says anything, just say you were tight.\'94\
\
\'93Quite. And the funny thing is I think I was tight.\'94\
\
\'93Come on,\'94 Brett said. \'93Are these poisonous things paid for? I must\
bathe before dinner.\'94\
\
We walked across the square. It was dark and all around the square were\
the lights from the caf\'e9s under the arcades. We walked across the gravel\
under the trees to the hotel.\
\
They went up-stairs and I stopped to speak with Montoya.\
\
\'93Well, how did you like the bulls?\'94 he asked.\
\
\'93Good. They were nice bulls.\'94\
\
\'93They\'92re all right\'94\'97Montoya shook his head\'97\'93but they\'92re not too good.\'94\
\
\'93What didn\'92t you like about them?\'94\
\
\'93I don\'92t know. They just didn\'92t give me the feeling that they were so\
good.\'94\
\
\'93I know what you mean.\'94\
\
\'93They\'92re all right.\'94\
\
\'93Yes. They\'92re all right.\'94\
\
\'93How did your friends like them?\'94\
\
\'93Fine.\'94\
\
\'93Good,\'94 Montoya said.\
\
I went up-stairs. Bill was in his room standing on the balcony looking\
out at the square. I stood beside him.\
\
\'93Where\'92s Cohn?\'94\
\
\'93Up-stairs in his room.\'94\
\
\'93How does he feel?\'94\
\
\'93Like hell, naturally. Mike was awful. He\'92s terrible when he\'92s tight.\'94\
\
\'93He wasn\'92t so tight.\'94\
\
\'93The hell he wasn\'92t. I know what we had before we came to the caf\'e9.\'94\
\
\'93He sobered up afterward.\'94\
\
\'93Good. He was terrible. I don\'92t like Cohn, God knows, and I think it was\
a silly trick for him to go down to San Sebastian, but nobody has any\
business to talk like Mike.\'94\
\
\'93How\'92d you like the bulls?\'94\
\
\'93Grand. It\'92s grand the way they bring them out.\'94\
\
\'93To-morrow come the Miuras.\'94\
\
\'93When does the fiesta start?\'94\
\
\'93Day after to-morrow.\'94\
\
\'93We\'92ve got to keep Mike from getting so tight. That kind of stuff is\
terrible.\'94\
\
\'93We\'92d better get cleaned up for supper.\'94\
\
\'93Yes. That will be a pleasant meal.\'94\
\
\'93Won\'92t it?\'94\
\
As a matter of fact, supper was a pleasant meal. Brett wore a black,\
sleeveless evening dress. She looked quite beautiful. Mike acted as\
though nothing had happened. I had to go up and bring Robert Cohn down.\
He was reserved and formal, and his face was still taut and sallow, but\
he cheered up finally. He could not stop looking at Brett. It seemed to\
make him happy. It must have been pleasant for him to see her looking so\
lovely, and know he had been away with her and that every one knew it.\
They could not take that away from him. Bill was very funny. So was\
Michael. They were good together.\
\
It was like certain dinners I remember from the war. There was much\
wine, an ignored tension, and a feeling of things coming that you could\
not prevent happening. Under the wine I lost the disgusted feeling and\
was happy. It seemed they were all such nice people.\
\
\
